 were maintained exactly as in the golden testbench.\\n6. **Advice:** The primary advice is to carefully parse the golden testbench to determine the *actual* expected interface and logic flow, as it supersedes the natural language specification when conflicts exist. Syntax errors in testbenches often stem from truncated or malformed statements, which must be meticulously repaired to maintain functional integrity.",\n    "interface": "module TopModule (\\n    input logic [3:0] x,\\n    output logic f\\n);\\nendmodule",\n    "testbench": "`timescale 1 ps/1 ps\\n`define OK 12\\n`define INCORRECT 13\\n\\n// --- Stimulus Generator ---\\nmodule stimulus_gen (\\n\\tinput clk,\\n\\toutput logic [3:0] x\\n);\\n\\t\\tinitial begin\\n\\t\\trepeat(100) @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\\n\\t\\tx <= $random;\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t#1 $finish;\\n\\tend\\n\\tendmodule\\n\\n// Assuming RefModule exists and matches the required interface\\nmodule RefModule (\\n    input logic [3:0] x,\\n    output logic f\\n);\\n    // Placeholder implementation for compilation, as its logic is not provided, \\n    // but its interface must match the testbench.\\n    assign f = x[0]; \\nendmodule\\n\\n// --- DUT Implementation (TopModule) ---\\n// Using the structure from previous_code for TopModule implementation\\nmodule TopModule (\\n    input logic [3:0] x,\\n    output logic f\\n);\\n\\t\\t// Combinational logic implementation derived directly from the K-map table.\\n\\t\\t// We map the K-map rows (x[3]x[2]) and columns (x[1]x[0]) to the 4-bit input x.\\n\\t\\t// d (don\'t care) values are set to 0 for this implementation.\\n\\t\\talways @* begin\\n\\t\\t\\tcase (x) \\n\\t\\t\\t\\t// Row 00 (x[3]x[2]=00)\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t4\'b0000: f = 1\'b0; // d\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t4\'b0001: f = 1\'b0; // 0\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t4\'b0011: f = 1\'b0; // d\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t4\'b0010: f = 1\'b0; // d\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t// Row 01 (x[3]x[2]=01)\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t4\'b0100: f = 1\'b0; // 0\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t4\'b0101: f = 1\'b0; /